that predates them.

01:13:40.850 --> 01:13:44.120
What we have is role
diversification.

01:13:44.120 --> 01:13:47.220
Real animals, real
organisms, are not just

01:13:47.220 --> 01:13:51.030
playing one formal prisoner's
dilemma game against each other

01:13:51.030 --> 01:13:52.870
at the same time.

01:13:52.870 --> 01:13:55.560
And by the time we, again,
get to the later lectures

01:13:55.560 --> 01:13:57.300
on aggression,
cooperation, all of that,

01:13:57.300 --> 01:14:00.820
we will not only see that things
get much more complicated when

01:14:00.820 --> 01:14:02.770
you're playing
simultaneous games,

01:14:02.770 --> 01:14:04.932
when you're playing a game
against one individual

01:14:04.932 --> 01:14:06.640
while you're playing
against another one,

01:14:06.640 --> 01:14:09.240
and then against
triangular circumstances.

01:14:09.240 --> 01:14:12.690
How play differs if you
know how many rounds

01:14:12.690 --> 01:14:14.910
you are playing against
the individual versus

01:14:14.910 --> 01:14:16.330
if you have no idea.

01:14:16.330 --> 01:14:18.560
How play differs
if, when you are

01:14:18.560 --> 01:14:20.530
about to play
against someone, you

01:14:20.530 --> 01:14:22.830
get to find out what
their behavior has

01:14:22.830 --> 01:14:25.660
been in the previous trials
with other individuals.

01:14:25.660 --> 01:14:29.200
In other words, if somebody
shows up with a reputation,

01:14:29.200 --> 01:14:31.940
we'll see this is a much
more complicated world

01:14:31.940 --> 01:14:33.370
of playing out these games.

01:14:33.370 --> 01:14:35.570
A much more realistic one.

01:14:35.570 --> 01:14:39.180
So we begin to see a first pass
at all this optimization stuff,

01:14:39.180 --> 01:14:40.710
and how great that all is.

01:14:40.710 --> 01:14:44.770
One final interesting addition
to this game theory world

01:14:44.770 --> 01:14:47.780
of thinking about behavior like
that, which came from a guy

01:14:47.780 --> 01:14:51.100
named James Holland,
who apparently-- might

01:14:51.100 --> 01:14:52.350
have a different first name.

01:14:52.350 --> 01:14:55.570
But Holland, apparently, as an
interesting piece in history,

01:14:55.570 --> 01:14:57.410
he's the person first
person to ever get

01:14:57.410 --> 01:14:59.670
a PhD in Computer Sciences.

01:14:59.670 --> 01:15:02.520
Which I think was in the late
50s, University of Michigan.

01:15:02.520 --> 01:15:05.980
Apparently, there are realms
of computer programmers

01:15:05.980 --> 01:15:07.400
who worship this guy.

01:15:07.400 --> 01:15:09.900
And he, like a lot of other
folks in that business,

01:15:09.900 --> 01:15:12.910
got interested in this
game theory evolution

01:15:12.910 --> 01:15:14.300
of optimal strategies.

01:15:14.300 --> 01:15:16.870
And he designed ways
of running all of this.

01:15:16.870 --> 01:15:18.910
And he introduced
a new ripple, which

01:15:18.910 --> 01:15:22.930
is the possibility of a
strategy suddenly changing.

01:15:22.930 --> 01:15:26.080
The possibility of a mutation.

01:15:26.080 --> 01:15:28.560
What he could then
study was mutations,

01:15:28.560 --> 01:15:31.290
how often they were
adaptive, how often they

01:15:31.290 --> 01:15:35.360
spread throughout the strategy
there, of individuals playing.

01:15:35.360 --> 01:15:38.120
How often they drove
the other strategies

01:15:38.120 --> 01:15:41.220
into extinction versus
ones that were quickly

01:15:41.220 --> 01:15:42.830
driven to extinction themselves.

01:15:42.830 --> 01:15:45.730
More cases where we are
getting these systems

01:15:45.730 --> 01:15:48.400
where maybe they're not just
metaphorically using terms

01:15:48.400 --> 01:15:49.580
from biology.

01:15:49.580 --> 01:15:52.670
Maybe they are exactly
modeling the same thing.

01:15:52.670 --> 01:15:55.690
And we will see more and
more evidence for that.

01:15:55.690 --> 01:15:58.170
OK, so reciprocal altruism.

01:15:58.170 --> 01:16:01.670
How would that play out in the
world of natural selection.

01:16:01.670 --> 01:16:04.520
Natural selection,
cooperative hunting.

01:16:04.520 --> 01:16:07.170
And there's lots of species
that have cooperative hunting.

01:16:07.170 --> 01:16:11.234
Wild dogs, jackals, some
other species as well.

01:16:11.234 --> 01:16:12.850
Clearly, that's
like the definition

01:16:12.850 --> 01:16:16.050
of cooperative hunting,
of reciprocal altruism,

01:16:16.050 --> 01:16:17.310
if they're not relatives.

01:16:17.310 --> 01:16:19.660
How would sexual
selection play out

01:16:19.660 --> 01:16:21.580
in the realm of
reciprocal altruism?

01:16:21.580 --> 01:16:23.210
A little bit less obvious there.

01:16:23.210 --> 01:16:25.660
That would be if you
and some non-relative

01:16:25.660 --> 01:16:28.330
spent an insane amount
of energy and time

01:16:28.330 --> 01:16:32.980
making sure you both look really
good before going to the prom.

01:16:32.980 --> 01:16:35.736
That would be sexual selection
working on reciprocal altruism

01:16:35.736 --> 01:16:36.650
system.

01:16:36.650 --> 01:16:40.160
So what we have now are
three building blocks.

01:16:40.160 --> 01:16:43.950
This whole trashing of it's
not survival of the fittest.

01:16:43.950 --> 01:16:46.537
It's not behaving for
the good of the species.

01:16:46.537 --> 01:16:48.370
It's not behaving for
the good of the group.

01:16:48.370 --> 01:16:49.980
But instead, these
three building

01:16:49.980 --> 01:16:54.430
blocks, the ways to optimize
as many copies of your genes

01:16:54.430 --> 01:16:56.290
in the next generation
as possible.

01:16:56.290 --> 01:16:59.620
Way number one,
individual selection,

01:16:59.620 --> 01:17:01.250
a version of selfish genes.

01:17:01.250 --> 01:17:04.500
Sometimes a chicken is an egg's
way of making another egg.

01:17:04.500 --> 01:17:07.260
Behavior is just a way of
getting copies of genes

01:17:07.260 --> 01:17:09.170
into the next generation.

01:17:09.170 --> 01:17:12.587
Piece number two, inclusive
fitness kin selection.

01:17:12.587 --> 01:17:14.420
That whole business,
that sometimes the best

01:17:14.420 --> 01:17:17.160
way of passing on copies
is to help relatives do it.

01:17:17.160 --> 01:17:19.270
And it's a function of
how related they are.

01:17:19.270 --> 01:17:23.850
The whole world of cooperation
more among related organisms

01:17:23.850 --> 01:17:25.330
than unrelated ones.

01:17:25.330 --> 01:17:28.150
And as we will see way
down the line, what

01:17:28.150 --> 01:17:30.480
is very challenging
in different species

01:17:30.480 --> 01:17:33.470
is, how do you figure out
who you are related to?

01:17:33.470 --> 01:17:36.970
And humans do it in a very
unique way that sets them up

01:17:36.970 --> 01:17:40.560
for being exploited in all
sorts of circumstances that

01:17:40.560 --> 01:17:44.470
begin to explain why culture
after culture, people

01:17:44.470 --> 01:17:48.920
are really not nice to thems,
and it flows along those lines.

01:17:48.920 --> 01:17:51.500
This is something we will
get to in a lot of detail.

01:17:51.500 --> 01:17:54.140
So degree of relatedness,
a lecture coming.

01:17:54.140 --> 01:17:56.020
How do you tell who
you're related to.

01:17:56.020 --> 01:17:58.440
But that second
piece, kin selection.

01:17:58.440 --> 01:18:00.800
Third piece,
reciprocal altruism.

01:18:00.800 --> 01:18:03.700
You scratch my back and
I'll scratch your back.

01:18:03.700 --> 01:18:06.775
And whenever possible, you want
to instead scratch your back,

01:18:06.775 --> 01:18:08.150
and they want to
make sure you're

01:18:08.150 --> 01:18:09.310
not scratching your back.

01:18:09.310 --> 01:18:11.020
Or whatever cheating counts as.

01:18:11.020 --> 01:18:13.730
But trying to cheat,
being vigilant against it,

01:18:13.730 --> 01:18:17.750
formal games where you can
optimize it, very complicated.

01:18:17.750 --> 01:18:20.360
And can you believe it, you
go out into the real world,

01:18:20.360 --> 01:18:23.140
and you find examples
of precisely that.

01:18:23.140 --> 01:18:25.830
Optimization with tit for
tat, isn't nature wonderful.

01:18:25.830 --> 01:18:27.470
It's gotta work that way.

01:18:27.470 --> 01:18:30.800
Then you begin to see how the
real world is more complicated.

01:18:30.800 --> 01:18:34.290
Multiple roles, naked mole
rats stuck in plumbing,

01:18:34.290 --> 01:18:36.940
