01:27:44.350 --> 01:27:48.050
You see female cuckoldry,
this great Victorian term.

01:27:48.050 --> 01:27:51.770
You see females cheating on
the fathers in this species,

01:27:51.770 --> 01:27:53.580
but not in species like this.

01:27:53.580 --> 01:27:58.060
Because the father is long gone
and three other counties there,

01:27:58.060 --> 01:27:59.430
courting somebody else.

01:27:59.430 --> 01:28:00.920
And it doesn't
matter, you're not

01:28:00.920 --> 01:28:02.370
going to get any help from him.

01:28:02.370 --> 01:28:04.650
In primate species
of this profile,

01:28:04.650 --> 01:28:06.650
you always see twinning.

01:28:06.650 --> 01:28:08.440
And they both survive.

01:28:08.440 --> 01:28:10.660
And what studies have
shown in these species,

01:28:10.660 --> 01:28:12.420
and we'll get to
them shortly, is

01:28:12.420 --> 01:28:16.434
after birth, in fact, the males
are expending more calories

01:28:16.434 --> 01:28:17.850
taking care of the
offspring, then

01:28:17.850 --> 01:28:22.570
the females go bail out on him
and go find some other hot guy.

01:28:22.570 --> 01:28:24.320
Which, in your species,
counts as some guy

01:28:24.320 --> 01:28:27.400
who looks even more like you
than he does in terms of what

01:28:27.400 --> 01:28:29.190
you want out of the individual.

01:28:29.190 --> 01:28:29.967
So that.

01:28:29.967 --> 01:28:31.050
So what have we done here?

01:28:31.050 --> 01:28:33.700
We've just gone through
applying these principles

01:28:33.700 --> 01:28:35.590
in this logical
way, and everybody

01:28:35.590 --> 01:28:38.550
from the very first step was
getting the right outcome.

01:28:38.550 --> 01:28:41.800
And go, and these are
exactly the profiles

01:28:41.800 --> 01:28:43.600
you find in certain species.

01:28:43.600 --> 01:28:46.420
Among social mammals,
these would be referred to

01:28:46.420 --> 01:28:48.770
as a tournament species.

01:28:48.770 --> 01:28:51.470
A tournament species,
whereas the one on the right

01:28:51.470 --> 01:28:55.730
is referred to as a pair
bonding, a monogamous species.

01:28:55.730 --> 01:28:58.420
Because in this one,
males and females

01:28:58.420 --> 01:29:01.840
stay together, because they
both have equivalent investment

01:29:01.840 --> 01:29:03.120
in taking care of the kids.

01:29:03.120 --> 01:29:04.000
All of that.

01:29:04.000 --> 01:29:05.830
What you have here
is this contrast

01:29:05.830 --> 01:29:10.010
between tournament species
and pair bonding species.

01:29:10.010 --> 01:29:13.020
Tournament species,
these are all the species

01:29:13.020 --> 01:29:16.690
where you get males with
big, bright plumage.

01:29:16.690 --> 01:29:19.660
These are peacocks,
these are all those birds

01:29:19.660 --> 01:29:22.640
and fish species where the
males are all brightly colored.

01:29:22.640 --> 01:29:25.000
What are the females
choosing for?

01:29:25.000 --> 01:29:28.580
Peacock feathers does not make
for a good peacock mother.

01:29:28.580 --> 01:29:31.860
Peacock feathers are signs
of being healthy enough

01:29:31.860 --> 01:29:33.640
that you can waste
lots of energy

01:29:33.640 --> 01:29:35.740
on these big stupid
pointless feathers.

01:29:35.740 --> 01:29:37.470
That's a sign of health.

01:29:37.470 --> 01:29:41.030
That's a sign of all I'm getting
from this peacock is genes,

01:29:41.030 --> 01:29:42.750
I might as well
go for good ones.

01:29:42.750 --> 01:29:44.250
That's the world
of peacocks, that's

01:29:44.250 --> 01:29:46.930
the world of chickens
with pecking orders,

01:29:46.930 --> 01:29:49.210
dominating like that,
lots of aggression.

01:29:49.210 --> 01:29:53.210
That's the world of primates
where, as in savanna baboons,

01:29:53.210 --> 01:29:55.560
the male is twice as
big as the female.

01:29:55.560 --> 01:30:00.010
Tournament species, where a
lot of passing on of genes

01:30:00.010 --> 01:30:03.570
is decided by male-male
aggression in the context

01:30:03.570 --> 01:30:07.950
of tournaments producing
massive amounts of variability

01:30:07.950 --> 01:30:09.440
in reproductive success.

01:30:09.440 --> 01:30:12.300
Where males are being selected
for being good at this,

01:30:12.300 --> 01:30:15.260
so they sure are being selected
for having big bodies, which

01:30:15.260 --> 01:30:16.814
winds up meaning
a shortened life

01:30:16.814 --> 01:30:17.980
span for a bunch of reasons.

01:30:17.980 --> 01:30:19.600
Females are choosing for that.

01:30:19.600 --> 01:30:21.620
These are guys who are
not using their energy

01:30:21.620 --> 01:30:23.840
on parental behavior,
thus you do not

01:30:23.840 --> 01:30:26.160
want to have twins if
you are a female baboon,

01:30:26.160 --> 01:30:28.030
and you do not want to
bail out on the kids

01:30:28.030 --> 01:30:30.170
because nobody else is
going to take care of them.

01:30:30.170 --> 01:30:33.020
Go and look at a
new primate species,

01:30:33.020 --> 01:30:36.100
and see this much of a
difference in skull size,

01:30:36.100 --> 01:30:38.260
and you'd just be able
to derive everything

01:30:38.260 --> 01:30:40.420
else about its social behavior.

01:30:40.420 --> 01:30:44.140
Meanwhile, these guys on the
right, pair bonding species.

01:30:44.140 --> 01:30:47.300
These are found among South
American monkeys, marmosets,

01:30:47.300 --> 01:30:48.180
tamarins.

01:30:48.180 --> 01:30:50.010
You put up a picture
of them, which

01:30:50.010 --> 01:30:51.866
