01:31:00.570 --> 01:31:04.310
with males with big, bright,
bizarre coloration on the face,

01:31:04.310 --> 01:31:06.700
and with antlers when
the females don't,

01:31:06.700 --> 01:31:09.681
and that whole world
of sexual dimorphism.

01:31:09.681 --> 01:31:11.180
You can't tell which
one is the male

01:31:11.180 --> 01:31:13.920
and which one is the female
marmoset by looking at them.

01:31:13.920 --> 01:31:16.180
You can't tell by seeing
how long they live.

01:31:16.180 --> 01:31:17.630
You can't tell by
how much they're

01:31:17.630 --> 01:31:19.180
taking care of the kids.

01:31:19.180 --> 01:31:22.180
You can't tell in terms of
their reproductive variability.

01:31:22.180 --> 01:31:24.560
That's a whole different
world of selection.

01:31:24.560 --> 01:31:27.950
All of the South American
tamarins and marmosets,

01:31:27.950 --> 01:31:30.010
the females always twin.

01:31:30.010 --> 01:31:31.710
They have a higher
rate of cuckoldry,

01:31:31.710 --> 01:31:33.400
of abandoning the kids.

01:31:33.400 --> 01:31:35.520
The males take as much
care, if not more,

01:31:35.520 --> 01:31:37.100
of the kids than
the female does.

01:31:37.100 --> 01:31:38.470
Very low levels of aggression.

01:31:38.470 --> 01:31:40.320
Same body size, same lifespan.

01:31:40.320 --> 01:31:43.020
All the males have low
degree of variability.

01:31:43.020 --> 01:31:43.880
How come?

01:31:43.880 --> 01:31:45.910
Because if you're
some marmoset male,

01:31:45.910 --> 01:31:49.150
you don't want to get 47
marmoset females pregnant.

01:31:49.150 --> 01:31:51.970
Because you are going to have
to take care of all the kids.

01:31:51.970 --> 01:31:55.010
Because as we will see way
down the line in lectures

01:31:55.010 --> 01:31:57.900
on parental behavior,
the wiring there is such

01:31:57.900 --> 01:32:01.310
is bonding with the offspring
and taking care of them.

01:32:01.310 --> 01:32:03.870
No wonder among
species like these,

01:32:03.870 --> 01:32:05.810
you have very low variability.

01:32:05.810 --> 01:32:08.100
All the males reproduce
once or twice.

01:32:08.100 --> 01:32:10.780
This is the world of 5%
of the guys accounting

01:32:10.780 --> 01:32:12.890
for 95% of the matings.

01:32:12.890 --> 01:32:16.160
This is totally
remarkable because again,

01:32:16.160 --> 01:32:17.320
that starting point.

01:32:17.320 --> 01:32:19.320
You start off here,
and you look at these,

01:32:19.320 --> 01:32:21.530
and oh, you can tell if
they were bipedal and were

01:32:21.530 --> 01:32:24.650
they diseased or malnourished,
simply by applying

01:32:24.650 --> 01:32:28.200
these principles of individual
selection, reciprocity,

01:32:28.200 --> 01:32:29.050
all of that.

01:32:29.050 --> 01:32:32.230
One factoid, you see
a new primate species,

01:32:32.230 --> 01:32:34.760
and you see one nursing
and one with a penis,

01:32:34.760 --> 01:32:37.820
and they're the same size or
there's difference in the size,

01:32:37.820 --> 01:32:40.850
and you already know all
about their social system.

01:32:40.850 --> 01:32:46.620
Very consistent across birds,
across fish, across primates.

01:32:46.620 --> 01:32:48.730
Of course, all of
those, this dichotomy

01:32:48.730 --> 01:32:52.210
between tournament species
and pair bonding species.

01:32:52.210 --> 01:32:54.570
As we will see
way down the line,

01:32:54.570 --> 01:32:57.540
among some species,
types of voles, rodents,

01:32:57.540 --> 01:33:01.060
that are famous in Hallmark
cards for their pair bonding,

01:33:01.060 --> 01:33:02.310
for their monogamy.

01:33:02.310 --> 01:33:04.560
As we'll see, they're
not quite as monogamous

01:33:04.560 --> 01:33:05.390
as you would think.

01:33:05.390 --> 01:33:09.190
But nonetheless, a general
structure like this.

01:33:09.190 --> 01:33:14.860
So, one asks expectedly, where
do humans fit in on this one?

01:33:14.860 --> 01:33:16.530
Where do humans fit?

01:33:16.530 --> 01:33:19.320
And the answer
is, complicatedly.

01:33:19.320 --> 01:33:22.820
Are we a tournament species,
are we a pair bonding species.

01:33:22.820 --> 01:33:24.240
What's up with that?

01:33:24.240 --> 01:33:28.520
What we will see is
we're kind of in between.

01:33:28.520 --> 01:33:31.310
When you look at the degree
of sexual dimorphism,

01:33:31.310 --> 01:33:34.440
we are not like baboons, but
we're sure not like marmosets.

01:33:34.440 --> 01:33:36.080
We're somewhere in the middle.

01:33:36.080 --> 01:33:39.530
Variability is somewhere
in the middle there.

01:33:39.530 --> 01:33:41.250
I'm not going near that one.

01:33:41.250 --> 01:33:44.200
Life span, the
dimorphism in lifespan

01:33:44.200 --> 01:33:46.880
tends to be in between.

01:33:46.880 --> 01:33:49.290
Parental behavior and
likelihood-- all of those,

01:33:49.290 --> 01:33:50.800
you look at a
number of measures.

01:33:50.800 --> 01:33:53.370
And by next lecture,
we'll be looking

01:33:53.370 --> 01:33:56.570
at some genetics of what
a monogamous species

01:33:56.570 --> 01:33:58.560
and tournament
species look like.

01:33:58.560 --> 01:34:00.780
And we're right in the middle.

01:34:00.780 --> 01:34:04.980
In other words, that explains
like 90% of literature.

01:34:04.980 --> 01:34:08.010
Because we're not a classic
tournament species and we're

01:34:08.010 --> 01:34:09.760
not a classic pair bonding one.

01:34:09.760 --> 01:34:12.790
We are terribly confused
in the middle there.

01:34:12.790 --> 01:34:17.250
And everything about
anthropology supports that.

01:34:17.250 --> 01:34:19.980
Most people on the
planet right now

01:34:19.980 --> 01:34:23.220
are in a form of
monogamous relationships

01:34:23.220 --> 01:34:28.000
in a culture that
demands monogamy.

01:34:28.000 --> 01:34:30.700
An awful lot of people who are
in monogamous relationships

01:34:30.700 --> 01:34:33.910
in such cultures aren't really
in monogamous relationships.

01:34:33.910 --> 01:34:38.850
Traditionally, most cultures on
this planet allowed polygamy.

01:34:38.850 --> 01:34:41.960
Nonetheless, in most of
those polygamous cultures,

01:34:41.960 --> 01:34:45.760
the majority of individuals
were pair bonded and monogamous.

01:34:45.760 --> 01:34:47.690
You get two different
versions of polygamy

01:34:47.690 --> 01:34:49.650
in different social
systems of humans.

01:34:49.650 --> 01:34:53.620
One is economic polygamy,
which is you're basically

01:34:53.620 --> 01:34:57.200
sitting around, and the
wealthiest guy in the village

01:34:57.200 --> 01:35:00.680
is the one who can have the
largest number of wives.

01:35:00.680 --> 01:35:02.910
An enormous skew in
reproductive success

01:35:02.910 --> 01:35:04.800
that's driven by economics.

01:35:04.800 --> 01:35:06.970
The other type is demographic.

01:35:06.970 --> 01:35:09.380
You have a culture
where, for example, you

01:35:09.380 --> 01:35:11.050
have a warrior class.

01:35:11.050 --> 01:35:14.570
Guys spend 10 years as
warriors-- worriers, warriors,

01:35:14.570 --> 01:35:15.920
New York City accent.

01:35:15.920 --> 01:35:17.870
As warriors, they don't worry.

01:35:17.870 --> 01:35:18.730
There's no anxiety.

01:35:18.730 --> 01:35:20.350
But they eventually worry
about getting a wife,

01:35:20.350 --> 01:35:22.450
because by the time they're
done being a warrior,

01:35:22.450 --> 01:35:24.060
they're like 25.

01:35:24.060 --> 01:35:26.330
And they marry someone
who's 13, which

01:35:26.330 --> 01:35:28.520
is what you see in a lot
of traditional cultures

01:35:28.520 --> 01:35:29.970
that follow that pattern.

01:35:29.970 --> 01:35:32.460
And at that point,
you've got a problem,

01:35:32.460 --> 01:35:35.260
which is an awful lot of
those guys have been killed

01:35:35.260 --> 01:35:38.220
over the course of 10
years of being involved

01:35:38.220 --> 01:35:41.030
in high levels of aggression
and 10 more years of life

01:35:41.030 --> 01:35:42.610
expectancy to catch up with you.

01:35:42.610 --> 01:35:44.640
There's is a shortage of males.

01:35:44.640 --> 01:35:48.000
So you see polygamy there
driven by demographics,

01:35:48.000 --> 01:35:50.660
and you see polygamy
driven by economics

01:35:50.660 --> 01:35:52.270
in other types of society.

01:35:52.270 --> 01:35:56.070
So most cultures on this
planet allow-- traditionally,

01:35:56.070 --> 01:35:57.690
before the
missionaries got them--

01:35:57.690 --> 01:36:00.530
most cultures on this
planet allow polygamy.

01:36:00.530 --> 01:36:03.520
Nonetheless, within most
polygamous cultures,

01:36:03.520 --> 01:36:06.270
the majority of people
are not polygamous.

01:36:06.270 --> 01:36:10.580
We have one really confused,
screwed up species here.

01:36:10.580 --> 01:36:14.160
Because we are halfway in
between in all sorts of these

01:36:14.160 --> 01:36:15.190
measures.

